Diet.Source: Duya et al. 2011 Fieldiana Life and Earth Sciences
PlantCat.Source: Duya et al. 2011 Fieldiana Life and Earth Sciences
PlantCat.Notes: Described as an insectivore/vermivore species. The PHYLACINE diet data was imputed, but based on other shrew-mice, this species is likely a strict invertivore. Therefore, we assign Invert as 100 (originally Invert as 88 and Plant as 12) and all other diet categories as 0.

Isotope data suggests a diet consisting primarily of submerged aquatic macrophytes with very little terrestrial plants, similar to muskrats and in contrast to extant beavers. Muskrats and extant beavers both have Herb as 100, so we assign Herb as 100 for this species.

Manualy added. Other Geocapromys are not included in out study because their ranges did not fall within a grid cell, so diet data was not automatically imputed. All 3 Geocapromys species in EltonTraits have diets of 30% Fruit and 70% PlantO.

ForStrat.Source: Cooke & Crowley 2018 Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology
ForStrat.Notes: Cooke & Crowley note the low frequency of specimens and suggest that this species may be relatively arboreal and thus less likely to fall into sinkholes.
PlantCat.Source: Cooke & Crowley 2018 Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology
PlantCat.Notes: Isotope data suggests folivory. We apply the 30:70 ratio of Fruit to Herb that we have for all hutias.

ForStrat.Source: Nguyen et al. 2014 Biodiversity Data Journal
PlantCat.Source: Nguyen et al. 2014 Biodiversity Data Journal; Scopin et al. 2011 Proceedings of the Zoological Institute RAS
PlantCat.Notes: Stomach samples have included leaves, buds, fruits, and roots, as well as corn kernels. However, the unique foregut of this species indicates folivory, and leaves make up the majority of samples, although seeds and underground plant parts have also been recorded. Following ElonTraits protocols and assuming that other plant parts (leaves, bud, roots) make a majority of the diet with fruits and seeds also consumed, we assign Fruit as 15, Seed as 15, and Herb as 70.

Diet.Source: Helgen, Leary, & Aplin 2010 American Museum Novitates
PlantCat.Source: Helgen, Leary, & Aplin 2010 American Museum Novitates
PlantCat.Notes: Members of Microhydromys are all assumed to have similar diets, primarily invertebrates. Both Microhydromys species are 100% invertivorous according to EltonTraits. PHYLACINE also has M. richardsoni as Invert 100 but imputed the diet for M. argentus. We assign Invert as 100 (originally Invert as 88, Vert as 1, and Plant as 11) and all other diet categories as 0.

PlantCat.Source: Carbot-Chanona, Eng-Ponce, & Gomez-Perez 2020 Boletin de la Sociedad Geologica Mexicana
PlantCat.Notes: Diet assumed to be similar to extant capybaras. We apply the 10:90 ratio of Fruit to Herb that we have for both extant capybara species.

ForStrat.Notes: Based on this species' exclusive diet of worms.
PlantCat.Notes: This species is a strictly eats worms, and it has specialized to the extent that it lacks molars. Therefore, we assign Invert as 100 (originally Invert as 80 and Plant as 20) and all other diet categories as 0.
